Kubernetes Aliases for Productivity

ðŸ”§ Kubernetes Tip of the Day: Boost your CLI speed with kubectl aliases!
Working with Kubernetes daily? Tired of typing long kubectl commands repeatedly?
Here are some handy aliases I use to save time and work efficiently in the terminal ðŸ‘‡

alias k='kubectl'
This is the most fundamental and widely used alias.

alias kgp='kubectl get pods'
alias kgs='kubectl get svc'
alias kga='kubectl get all -A'
alias kgn='kubectl get nodes'
alias kaf='kubectl apply -f'
alias kg='k get'
alias kgp='kg pods'
alias kgd='kg deploy'
alias kgs='kg svc'
alias kgi='kg ingress'
alias kgn='kg nodes'
alias kgcm='kg configmaps'
alias kgsec='kg secrets'
alias kgns='kg namespaces'
alias kgcrd='kg crd'
alias krh='k rollout history'
alias krs='k rollout status'
alias kru='k rollout undo'
alias klo='k logs -f'
# Tail logs of a podalias kex='k exec -it'
# Execute a shell in a podalias ksyslo='k logs -n kube-system -f'
# Tail kube-system logs

âœ… Add these in your ~/.bashrc or ~/.zshrc, then run:

# source ~/.bashrc
Youâ€™ll be amazed how much time these save when you're deep in debugging, rolling updates, or managing workloads across multiple namespaces!

ðŸ‘‰ Add your aliases: Append the alias definitions to the end of the file.
Basic Alias Syntax: alias <shortcut_name>='<full_command>'
Source the file (or open a new terminal): After adding aliases, they won't be active until you load the updated configuration.

source ~/.bashrc
# OR
source ~/.bash_aliases # if you used a separate file
